  "relevant_summary": "Maintaining existing roosts within bridges can support continuity of use: a Daubenton\u2019s bat maternity colony continued to roost in similar numbers after crevices were retained during repairs in Ireland, and Yuma myotis and Mexican free\u2011tailed bats recolonised most maintained bridge roosts in similar numbers after replacement works in the USA; however, pallid bats did not return to maintained roosts in that review [1966]. Creating new roosting spaces in bridges to replace lost roosts led to recolonization by bats in similar or greater numbers at four of eight sites in a USA review, indicating variable success across sites [1967]. Providing alternative roosts (bat houses) during bridge replacement was less successful in the USA review: bat houses were used by fewer Mexican free\u2011tailed bats than the original roost at one site and were not used at all at three sites [2942].",
