  "query": "How does the evidence for legally protecting bat habitats compare to legally protecting bats during development activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Legally protecting bat habitats: Five studies (Europe and India) evaluated this action [2045]. Two replicated studies found no difference in bat species richness between protected and unprotected forests or fragments, while one replicated study in France found more bat species in protected sites [2045]. One replicated study in India found similar species composition between protected and unprotected forest fragments [2045]. Four studies reported abundance/activity outcomes: Daubenton\u2019s bat activity was higher over rivers on farms in protected areas than unprotected areas in the UK; common noctule activity was higher in protected forests but overall bat activity did not differ; two studies (France, India) found higher overall bat activity and greater numbers of bats in protected sites/forests than unprotected sites/forests [2045]. One study in Spain found the distributions of 10 of 11 bat species overlapped with designated protected areas more than expected by chance [2045]. Legally protecting bats during development: Four UK studies evaluated licensing during development [1935]. No studies measured community or population responses [1935]. Two reviews reported behavioural/compliance outcomes: development licences for bats more than doubled over three years in Scotland, and 81% of licensees did not carry out post-development monitoring [1935]. Three studies reported roost impacts: one review found licensed development activities had a negative impact with 68% of roosts destroyed; a replicated before-and-after study found 5/28 compensation roosts were used, with two used by similar or greater numbers of bats after development; another review found 31\u201367% of compensation roosts provided under licence were used [1935].",
