  "relevant_summary": "Studies within building developments have evaluated three alternatives to bat exclusion: creating alternative roosts, relocating access points, and retaining existing roosts/access points. Creating alternative roosts: Across 11 studies, some provided bat houses or a bat wall that were not used after exclusion, while other work reported bat boxes or lofts/barns used at 13\u201374% of development sites, with maternity use at one of 19 sites; before-and-after studies found purpose-built roosts used in higher or similar numbers in three of five cases and lower in two, and one review found replacement roosts were four times less likely to be used than roosts retained during development [949]. Relocating access points: Two before-and-after studies found fewer brown long-eared bats used a roost after access points were relocated with no bats observed flying through them in one case, and few lesser horseshoe bats used an alternative \u2018bend\u2019 access design but numbers increased after a \u2018straight\u2019 design was installed [946]. Retaining existing roosts/access points: Three studies reported similar numbers of brown long-eared bats roosting after access points were retained during renovations; four of nine retained roosts were used as maternity colonies with similar or greater numbers in two cases after development; and a review found bats used two-thirds of retained/modified roosts after development and that retained roosts were more likely to be used than newly created ones [947].",
