{
  "query": "As an alternative to increasing turbine cut-in speeds, what other operational changes can reduce bat mortality at wind farms?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from operational adjustments other than raising cut\u2011in speeds indicates: (1) Preventing turbine blades from turning at low wind speeds (\u201cfeathering\u201d) reduced bat fatalities in five of six studies in the USA and Canada, though one study found no reduction [970]. (2) Slowing blade rotation at low wind speeds reduced bat fatalities in a replicated, randomized, controlled study in Canada [2939]. (3) Automatically reducing blade rotation when bat activity is predicted to be high reduced bat fatalities in two replicated studies in Germany and the USA, for all bats combined and for several species [971]. (4) Using ultrasonic deterrents at turbines showed mixed outcomes across three replicated, randomized, controlled USA studies, with some trials reporting fewer fatalities (e.g., 21\u201351% fewer in one year; 2% more to 64% fewer the next) and species\u2011specific responses [968].",
  "action_ids": [
