{
  "query": "What are the outcomes and success rates associated with ex-situ bat conservation actions like captive breeding and rehabilitation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence on ex\u2011situ bat conservation is limited for captive breeding and more developed for rehabilitation. No studies were found that evaluated breeding bats in captivity to supplement wild populations affected by white\u2011nose syndrome [2009], and no studies were found that evaluated the effects of releasing captive\u2011bred bats on bat populations [2039]. Four studies evaluated rehabilitating injured/orphaned bats: 70\u201390% of hand\u2011reared pipistrelle bats survived for at least 4\u201314 days after release, with six of 21 joining wild colonies [2054]; pipistrelles that flew in a large flight cage for longer periods before release survived longer and were more active than those with shorter or small\u2011enclosure flight [2054]; 13% of ringed hand\u2011reared pipistrelles were found alive in bat boxes 38 days to almost four years after release [2054]; two orphaned greater spear\u2011nosed bats survived over three months in captivity and increased in body weight and size to normal within 60 days [2054].",
